<h2>Salary Arbitrage Calculator</h2>

<h3>How the Salary Arbitrage Calculator Works</h3>
<p>The Salary Arbitrage calculator answers one question: if you earn a certain salary in a specific US city, how much would you need to earn in a foreign country to maintain the same standard of living?</p>

<p>The calculation uses three data points:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Your US city's Regional Price Parity (RPP)</strong> from the US Bureau of Economic Analysis. This measures how expensive your city is relative to the US national average. A city with RPP of 1.15 is 15% more expensive than average.</li>
<li><strong>The destination country's Purchasing Power Parity (PPP)</strong> from the World Bank. This measures how many units of local currency are needed to buy the same goods that one US dollar buys in the United States.</li>
<li><strong>The current exchange rate</strong> between USD and the local currency, retrieved from World Bank datasets and exchange-rate providers. Exchange rate data is refreshed regularly and cached for up to 24 hours to improve performance.</li>
</ul>

<h3>The Formula</h3>
<p>Price Level = Country PPP / Exchange Rate</p>
<p>Purchasing Power Multiplier = (1 / Price Level) x City RPP</p>
<p>Equivalent Income = Your Income / Multiplier</p>
<p>Annual Savings = Your Income - Equivalent Income (when working remotely)</p>

<h3>Example</h3>
<p>If a destination country has a purchasing power multiplier of 2.0, a person earning $100,000 in the United States could experience a standard of living similar to someone earning approximately $50,000 locally. If that person continues earning their US income while living abroad, the difference represents a cost-of-living advantage of $50,000 per year.</p>

<h3>Important Limitations</h3>
<p>The Salary Arbitrage calculator assumes you maintain your US income while paying local costs. Results show your cost-of-living advantage, not your actual after-tax savings. Individual results will vary based on lifestyle, neighborhood, family size, and personal spending habits. Taxes, both US and local, are not factored into the calculation.</p>

<h2>Why Results May Differ</h2>
<p>The calculator compares countries using national economic datasets and standardized assumptions. Actual living costs can vary significantly depending on city, neighborhood, housing choices, family size, healthcare needs, lifestyle preferences, and local tax obligations.</p>
<p>Results are best used as a starting point for research, not as a precise financial forecast. We recommend verifying costs with local sources and consulting relevant professionals before making relocation decisions.</p>

<h2>Quality of Life Score</h2>

<h3>How the Score Is Calculated</h3>
<p>Each country receives a Quality of Life Score from 0 to 100, based on eight metrics weighted as follows:</p>
<ul>
<li>Safety: 25%</li>
<li>Healthcare: 20%</li>
<li>Happiness: 15%</li>
<li>Human Development Index: 15%</li>
<li>Pollution: 8%</li>
<li>Unemployment: 7%</li>
<li>Internet Speed: 5%</li>
<li>Traffic: 5%</li>
</ul>

<h3>Grade Scale</h3>
<ul>
<li>A: 85% and above</li>
<li>B: 70% to 84%</li>
<li>C: 55% to 69%</li>
<li>D: 40% to 54%</li>
<li>F: Below 40%</li>
</ul>

<h2>Individual Metrics</h2>

<h3>Safety</h3>
<p>Source: Global Peace Index (Institute for Economics and Peace). A composite measure of societal safety, ongoing conflict, and militarization, scored on a 1.0-5.0 scale (lower is more peaceful) and converted to our 1-10 scoring system.</p>

<h3>Healthcare</h3>
<p>Source: UHC Service Coverage Index (World Bank/WHO). Measures coverage of essential health services across 14 tracer indicators, scored 0-100 and converted to our 1-10 scoring system.</p>

<h3>Happiness</h3>
<p>Source: World Happiness Report via Our World in Data. The WHR score runs from 0 to 10 and is used directly as the metric score.</p>

<h3>Pollution</h3>
<p>Source: Numbeo Pollution Index. Lower scores are better. Converted using a stepped scale where scores below 30 receive 10/10.</p>

<h3>Unemployment</h3>
<p>Source: World Bank. Lower unemployment rates receive higher scores. Rates below 3% receive 10/10.</p>

<h3>Internet Speed</h3>
<p>Source: Speedtest Global Index via Wikipedia. Speeds above 250 Mbps receive 10/10. Speeds below 60 Mbps receive 5/10.</p>

<h3>Human Development Index</h3>
<p>Source: UNDP Human Development Index via Our World in Data. A composite measure combining life expectancy, education levels, and income per capita, calibrated on a 0.0-1.0 scale and converted to our 1-10 scoring system. Replaces GDP growth as a more direct proxy for overall standard of living.</p>

<h3>Traffic</h3>
<p>Source: Numbeo Traffic Index. Lower traffic time indices receive higher scores.</p>

<h2>Mobility Metrics</h2>
<p>We also track four relocation-related metrics for each country:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Visa Access:</strong> Number of days a US passport holder can stay without a visa, sourced from the Passport Index dataset on GitHub.</li>
<li><strong>English Proficiency:</strong> EF English Proficiency Index score. Countries where English is the primary native language are marked as Native English.</li>
<li><strong>Tax System:</strong> Whether the country uses worldwide taxation (taxes all income regardless of source), territorial taxation (taxes only local income), or has no personal income tax. Compiled from public tax authority information and updated annually. High-level classification intended for comparison purposes only. Tax rules vary by individual circumstance and may change. Consult a qualified tax advisor before making decisions based on this information.</li>
<li><strong>Digital Nomad Visa:</strong> Whether the country offers an official visa program for remote workers. Sourced from Citizen Remote.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Data Updates</h2>
<p>We update all quality of life and mobility data quarterly. Each update pulls the latest available figures from each source using direct API calls and structured data downloads. Purchasing power and exchange-rate data are retrieved from public APIs and cached for up to 24 hours to improve performance.</p>

